    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "Explain why …",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "The Section B command. It asks for REASONS, not a story. Give two or three developed causes, each with specific evidence and a clear explanation of how it produced the outcome, then judge which mattered most. Each essay is worth [10]; you answer two of the three offered."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "How far do these sources support this view?",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "The command in part (e), worth [8]. 'How far' means you must reach a judgement on a scale — largely, partly, or hardly — after grouping the sources for and against the claim, weighing their provenance, and adding your own knowledge."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "How useful is this source?",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "A command asking you to weigh both CONTENT and PROVENANCE and to state what the source is useful FOR. A one-sided source is not useless: it is strong evidence of the view its author wanted others to hold."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "How reliable is this source?",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "A command asking whether the source can be trusted as evidence for this particular enquiry. Test who made it, when and why, then check its content against your own knowledge. Give a two-sided judgement, not a blanket 'it is biased'."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "What can you learn from this source?",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "The inference command. You must draw a conclusion the source implies but does not state directly, and support it with a short quotation. Copying the source out earns nothing."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "How surprised are you by this source?",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "A command requiring a two-sided, evidence-based answer: surprised because of what the source says, but not surprised once you consider who wrote it, when and why. Cross-reference against your own knowledge or another source."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "Provenance",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "The origin of a source: WHO produced it, WHEN, for WHOM and WHY. Provenance drives every judgement question — purpose, reliability, utility and surprise — so read a source's attribution before you read its content."
    },
    {
      "kind": "definition",
      "term": "Own knowledge (contextual knowledge)",
      "topic": "Exam skills",
      "body": "The historical detail you bring from outside the sources. Part (e) requires it, and it must do a job: explain why a source says what it says, test whether a claim is accurate, or supply what no source mentions. One precise fact used well beats a page of narrative."
    }
